explain or sell to, say, like, my GM. Like, we're going to invest a lot of time on,

00:23:42.560 --> 00:23:50.640
you know, working on computer vision. It may or may not work. And you're not going to see,

00:23:50.640 --> 00:23:56.400
like, a direct outcome of that project. But if it does, then it's going to be extremely valuable

00:23:56.400 --> 00:24:01.119
and it's going to be a significant advantage. But, like, I can't promise that. So I try to protect,

00:24:01.119 --> 00:24:06.000
like, that 20% time of just, like, this is just, like, learning. This is just personal development.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:12.479
This is experimental. And, like, yes, it will, you know, projects that we come up with and

00:24:12.479 --> 00:24:19.760
experiments that we do are kind of geared towards understanding the game of basketball better and

00:24:19.760 --> 00:24:24.880
to gain a competitive edge but are a little bit more closely aligned with, you know, that technical

00:24:26.160 --> 00:24:33.359
maintenance. So that's about, like, one day a week. And it's a little bit more flexible

00:24:33.359 --> 00:24:40.800
during our off-season push draft in the summer before training camp. And then we kind of have

00:24:40.800 --> 00:24:50.400
to balance, like, most of my team has been in basketball for many years. So we can kind of

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:55.520
anticipate, like, what the cadence of the season, like, what are the kind of questions can we either,

00:24:55.520 --> 00:25:04.880
like, anticipate and build out, like, what is, like, okay, like, we didn't crash the glass

00:25:05.439 --> 00:25:12.719
well enough. Like, we know, like, what the question is going to be the next day. And so,

00:25:12.719 --> 00:25:19.119
like, we have resources of here's the study that we did a year ago on this question. Here we've

00:25:19.119 --> 00:25:24.959
applied new data to it now. This is what we might recommend or this is what we would look into.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:33.359
And then, like, the one-off requests, we try to be pretty, like, on top of that depending

00:25:33.359 --> 00:25:42.479
on who's asking. And I think, like, that comes more from organizational structure and having

00:25:42.479 --> 00:25:48.719
strong leadership from the top and, like, a lot of buy-in, which I feel very, very fortunate to have.

00:25:52.479 --> 00:25:56.400
But also approachability is really important. So I would, like, I wouldn't want

00:25:57.599 --> 00:26:02.719
our department to feel inaccessible or anybody in our department to feel inaccessible even to

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:12.800
like the new grad basketball operations assistant. Frequently we've gotten questions of,

00:26:12.800 --> 00:26:16.319
like, oh, I'm really interested in what you're doing. I can even be, like, super

00:26:19.040 --> 00:26:27.599
beginner. Like, how do I, like, I have this question with X domain. Like, how would I

00:26:27.599 --> 00:26:35.040
start to learn R? Or, like, can you show me how to query the database? Like, what does that look

00:26:35.040 --> 00:26:42.880
like? And so we try to, like, build tools to empower different levels of users, both from

00:26:42.880 --> 00:26:48.880
their role but also their comfort with technology and to make sure that there's not this hard line

00:26:48.880 --> 00:26:56.880
between R&D and basketball. And then there's something the former director of R&D for the

00:26:56.880 --> 00:27:02.000
Milwaukee Bucks recently told me. He's like, I don't have a tech job. I have a basketball job.

00:27:03.040 --> 00:27:08.319
And I thought, oh, I've never really thought. I've thought it more like I have a tech job in a

00:27:08.319 --> 00:27:14.160
basketball team. And I think that's really more, like, a difference of philosophy of, like, how do

00:27:14.160 --> 00:27:23.199
you protect that and also how do you make sure that it's a goal, right? Like, the goal in basketball

00:27:23.199 --> 00:27:28.719
is the same as any other business, which is to succeed. Like, it's just a little bit more literal

00:27:28.719 --> 00:27:39.199
for us, like, to win. I really like that idea of protecting 20% of your team's time.

00:27:40.640 --> 00:27:47.040
And I know that can be so hard sometimes, too. So how do you actually go about doing that in practice?

00:27:47.040 --> 00:28:01.119
Personally, I try to make sure that I have, like, literally, like, 20% of my time during the week

00:28:01.119 --> 00:28:06.560
logged on some other, like, research or development initiative that I'm interested in.

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:12.560
It's very difficult to do during the season because we play games on weekends. We play games

00:28:12.560 --> 00:28:21.359
late at night. And it's almost, it feels a little unreasonable to say this is a 9-5 job, but also

00:28:21.359 --> 00:28:28.400
you need to show up at the arena at 6.30 or go straight from the practice facility to the arena

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:38.239
and show up the next morning. So we're pretty relaxed on, like, you're responsible for managing

00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:42.640
how you want to see your time. And, like, there are only, like,

00:28:42.640 --> 00:28:47.040
true, like, real emergencies, and they're not going to come from our department.

00:28:49.439 --> 00:28:54.000
Thank you. I see there's a few anonymous questions coming in, too. And one was,

00:28:54.560 --> 00:29:00.479
how do you see sports analytics evolve over the long term? Is it more proprietary

00:29:00.479 --> 00:29:04.959
advanced algorithms or more proprietary data or something else?

00:29:05.920 --> 00:29:13.920
Hmm. So there's this book called The MVP Machine, and it's about player development

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:20.479
in baseball. And I think that the biggest advances in sports analytics are going to be

00:29:21.839 --> 00:29:30.000
moving in that direction. And, like, how do you empower your, quote, unquote, end users,

00:29:30.319 --> 00:29:41.439
end users, your players or even your front office to grow using database insights?

00:29:43.439 --> 00:29:53.119
I think that in basketball, because we are relatively small compared to a data team for,

00:29:53.119 --> 00:30:00.160
say, baseball, which will have, you know, departments in the dozens, like a true startup,

00:30:01.520 --> 00:30:14.160
that we will probably remain more of, like, the interlocutors and some teams who are interested in,

00:30:14.160 --> 00:30:26.239
like, building out more models or taking on new experimental technical projects. I think that'll

00:30:26.239 --> 00:30:33.119
be more of a team prerogative rather than a trend. And, like, that advantage is going to be the same

00:30:33.119 --> 00:30:42.239
advantage that any team has in filling personnel, right? Like, it's how much money do you have to

00:30:42.239 --> 00:31:01.199
spend? But I do think that vendors and, like, the ability to not necessarily deliver modeling and

00:31:01.199 --> 00:31:09.680
insights to a team, but doing a lot of the processing power that would be expensive for us

00:31:10.479 --> 00:31:25.839
and taking care of the sort of things that maybe a general manager doesn't, like, can't see the

00:31:25.839 --> 00:31:32.000
immediate impact. So, like, my example of, like, I would love for my 20% time project to be working

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:40.800
on computer vision projects, but is that if there were a vendor that could provide that,

00:31:42.319 --> 00:31:47.280
that might be a more efficient use of both our time and resources.

00:31:49.760 --> 00:31:54.719
Thank you. I see there were quite a few other questions in the chat, too, and

00:31:55.359 --> 00:31:59.199
Bala, you had a question around data privacy. Would you want to jump in?

00:32:02.160 --> 00:32:11.280
Yeah. So, I just want to understand how you keep tab on various data regulations,

00:32:12.079 --> 00:32:15.920
especially I'm sure US has, each state has their own regulation. So,

00:32:16.479 --> 00:32:19.760
how do you manage the metadata? How do you share models or,

00:32:21.839 --> 00:32:23.599
because it's data is key for everything.

00:32:23.599 --> 00:32:24.800
Data is key for everything.

00:32:26.319 --> 00:32:31.920
Right. I mean, that's all proprietary and in-house. I'm not sure how you mean.

00:32:33.439 --> 00:32:41.040
So, the data basically would be associated with a player or a team. So, team might be

00:32:41.680 --> 00:32:45.040
all right because it's a rolled up heuristic data, which is fine.

00:32:45.040 --> 00:32:45.280
Right.

00:32:45.280 --> 00:32:48.640
But if it is with the player, then you might need to,

00:32:49.199 --> 00:32:55.199
in Europe, we have GDPR. So, we have to be compliant and there are different data

00:32:55.199 --> 00:33:01.839
policies that we need to go through to use that data. I'm not aware how it is done in US. So,

00:33:01.839 --> 00:33:03.920
that's where my curiosity came.

00:33:04.959 --> 00:33:11.680
Sure. So, the NBA Players Association has very strict regulations for

00:33:12.319 --> 00:33:17.680
how and what kind of data we can collect. So,

00:33:20.479 --> 00:33:25.839
the inferences that we make from the data sets that we subscribe to or collect ourselves like

00:33:25.839 --> 00:33:34.160
that, that is, that's totally fine. But for instance, like you can't put a tracking chip

00:33:34.719 --> 00:33:42.640
in a ball. You can't have a player wear wearables in-game. They have to give

00:33:42.640 --> 00:33:46.640
consent to do that and then only within a particular context.

00:33:48.959 --> 00:33:59.680
And so, because we're really only dealing with 20-some, including RG League players,

00:34:00.640 --> 00:34:05.040
a pretty limited set of players.

00:34:09.919 --> 00:34:17.040
But have you thought through when it comes to scale, maybe five or 10 years down the line?

00:34:19.040 --> 00:34:23.760
Again, this question might be of relevance, right? Because right now you're talking about

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:30.719
a very small data set, which could be easily managed. But if you're thinking about like

00:34:30.719 --> 00:34:36.800
five years down the line, getting all the players' data and systemically capturing it rather than

00:34:37.840 --> 00:34:42.479
someone manually entering it, all these things would come into play, right? Or

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:46.399
your team has not thought through that state?

00:34:46.879 --> 00:34:56.239
Well, I think that we're talking about a couple of different sources for data.

00:34:58.639 --> 00:35:07.360
And yeah, like I'm struggling with this because I'm definitely in my team brain right now.

00:35:08.560 --> 00:35:12.719
So, it's really like not a question of going to scale because, you know,

00:35:12.719 --> 00:35:19.679
we work at the service of these players, of these teams, and like we wouldn't be able to

00:35:19.679 --> 00:35:22.879
productionize or build a product that, you know, went public.

00:35:25.919 --> 00:35:31.439
I see in terms of this data and the kinds of data that you use,

00:35:31.439 --> 00:35:36.560
Frank just had a question in the chat as well. Frank, do you want to jump in?

00:35:36.639 --> 00:35:40.000
I see Tatsu has love for this as well.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:48.159
Yeah, so it's directly related here. All the on-court stuff makes a ton of sense to me. Like,

00:35:48.159 --> 00:35:57.120
that's pretty clear. I'm always super interested in the player behaviors, or like really anyone's

00:35:57.120 --> 00:36:03.520
consumer behaviors, player behaviors. And so, I'm always super interested in the player behaviors

00:36:03.600 --> 00:36:08.719
really anyone's consumer behaviors, player behaviors. And as we get more data there,

00:36:08.719 --> 00:36:12.479
right, like I actually don't have my whoop on today, but right, like if I'm wearing my whoop,

00:36:12.479 --> 00:36:17.520
I can help to a certain extent, right? There's some inaccuracies in the data and their models

00:36:17.520 --> 00:36:23.120
as well, but like I can start to make better decisions about, right, should I go easier on

00:36:23.120 --> 00:36:28.159
my run today? Should I go harder? And I'm wondering, like, do you and your team support

00:36:28.800 --> 00:36:35.199
some of that stuff? And then it makes me wonder, like, how, it's cool, but then, like, how real

00:36:35.199 --> 00:36:39.360
time can you get with that, right? Like, can you make different decisions right before the game

00:36:39.360 --> 00:36:43.120
starts to say, like, hey, this player, right, like look at their data. They're telling me they're

00:36:43.120 --> 00:36:49.840
fine, but if I'm the coach, like I want to make a different decision about play time start lineup.

00:36:49.840 --> 00:37:01.199
I don't know how those decisions get made. Yeah. We have, like, a very robust and excellent

00:37:01.199 --> 00:37:06.959
player performance staff that does address, like, more of the, like, physiological and athletic

00:37:07.919 --> 00:37:15.040
questions, like that data. But, you know, I was saying, like, a lot of this requires player

00:37:15.040 --> 00:37:22.320
consent and, like, player willingness to opt in because you can't just say, like, well, like,

00:37:22.320 --> 00:37:29.840
take the example of sleep. Like, sleep is such a huge concern in the NBA because we play 82 regular

00:37:29.840 --> 00:37:35.280
season games. And so the travel distance, like if you're playing games every other night or back to

00:37:35.280 --> 00:37:41.840
back and you're flying from New York to San Francisco to San Antonio, that is such a huge

00:37:41.840 --> 00:37:48.800
strain on your ability to perform at an elite level. How do you monitor, like, okay, like,

00:37:48.800 --> 00:37:55.280
maybe you're not going to, maybe you need to rest or maybe, like, you shouldn't play

00:37:57.760 --> 00:38:04.159
at, you know, at an extremely hard level during practice, things like that.

00:38:06.800 --> 00:38:11.679
And I think that to previous question's point of, like, what's the next direction in sports

00:38:11.679 --> 00:38:17.040
analytics? It is this kind of, like, behavioral question of, like, one, how do you get players

00:38:17.040 --> 00:38:24.239
to opt in? Personally, I think that it has to be, like, it can't be surveillance analytics.

00:38:24.239 --> 00:38:29.919
It has to be, what do I, like, what am I going to get out of this? And what do I want the team

00:38:29.919 --> 00:38:34.800
to know? And it becomes kind of tricky because, like, you want to optimize as a player,

00:38:35.040 --> 00:38:41.600
how am I going to perform, right? But you also need to be very careful of exposing,

00:38:42.399 --> 00:38:50.879
like, certain data to your team because it can affect where, you know, how much

00:38:50.879 --> 00:38:57.120
your next contract might be or if they know something about, you know, an injury I have,

00:38:57.120 --> 00:39:01.120
are they going to try and trade me? Like, how much leverage do I have?

00:39:01.679 --> 00:39:06.639
Got it. Yeah, the, and those trade-offs make sense.

00:39:09.040 --> 00:39:13.439
I like that idea of framing it, though, as what am I going to get out of it? Like,

00:39:13.439 --> 00:39:20.239
thinking of how we can all use that, even not with, like, players, but business stakeholders as well.

00:39:23.040 --> 00:39:27.760
I see there are a lot of other questions earlier. Mark, you had a question about,

00:39:27.919 --> 00:39:34.000
like, when you need to hire another full-time person. Do you want to jump in and add some context

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:41.360
there? Sorry, I was on mute. Yeah, I know you mentioned you have, like, a super or pretty

00:39:41.360 --> 00:39:47.120
small team, and this is tangentially related to Mike's question about balancing priorities.

00:39:47.919 --> 00:39:54.239
I guess, when do you, like, what's the cutoff between we have, you know,

00:39:54.959 --> 00:40:00.959
like, what's the cutoff between we have all these different priorities, and some of them we can push

00:40:00.959 --> 00:40:07.439
back, and some of them, you know, we'll just communicate that these are lesser versus,

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:13.840
hey, we need to accomplish all of this stuff, and we need to either expand the team or,

00:40:13.840 --> 00:40:16.399
you know, offload something to a different team.

00:40:17.360 --> 00:40:24.639
We always need at least one extra person, I think, both on the engineering side and on the data side.

00:40:27.439 --> 00:40:37.120
But a model, I think, that is maybe more successful for us is we almost have

00:40:39.120 --> 00:40:44.959
technical translators embedded in certain departments within basketball. So, we have a

00:40:45.120 --> 00:40:51.919
director of coaching analytics who's the main liaison with the coaching staff, and he sits on

00:40:51.919 --> 00:40:59.919
the bench at every game and provides in-game analysis, but he also does, you know, modeling

00:40:59.919 --> 00:41:07.760
specifically related to gameplay. And I think a reasonable question is, like, should that be one

00:41:07.760 --> 00:41:17.520
role? Should it be, you know, distinct roles? How do you kind of merge a team if it were distinct?

00:41:18.800 --> 00:41:24.639
And then, like, what about departments that don't have that embedded technical person? So, like,

00:41:24.639 --> 00:41:29.840
our cap and strategy group is two people, but when I was in Philadelphia, cap and strategy was

00:41:30.879 --> 00:41:34.719
technically part of my department. We were officially, when I started, before we

00:41:34.879 --> 00:41:42.479
we converted to research and development, we were strategy and analytics. And so,

00:41:44.959 --> 00:41:53.520
yeah, it's always tough because we're very lean, and it's almost like there are too many hats for

00:41:54.320 --> 00:42:02.719
for one head, but at the end of the day, like, you're essentially a consulting group

00:42:02.719 --> 00:42:11.199
embedded with a team, and you have to respond to that more so than, you know, technical prerogatives

00:42:11.199 --> 00:42:18.399
that you might have as a team and kind of negotiate, like, I think that the payoff, if we

00:42:18.399 --> 00:42:28.399
invest in this research direction or if we build out this tool, then we'll save both our

00:42:28.399 --> 00:42:33.600
time as well as our stakeholders' time. So, not a satisfying answer, I think.

00:42:38.560 --> 00:42:43.520
Yeah, I don't think that it's solved anywhere, and it's maybe not solved even by more people.

00:42:43.520 --> 00:42:49.840
My group in Philadelphia, we used to claim that we were 10, but that also included

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:54.959
outside consultants who worked in academia and at Google Brain.

00:42:56.719 --> 00:43:03.600
And, you know, the work that our consultants did certainly dovetailed with the work that

00:43:03.600 --> 00:43:11.040
we did, but it wasn't, they're kind of insulated from the demands that those of us who are

00:43:11.040 --> 00:43:16.159
directly embedded with the team and have front office roles or coaching roles would have to support.

00:43:17.040 --> 00:43:22.719
So, I don't know if maybe that's a better model or, you know, maybe rather than directly, you

00:43:22.719 --> 00:43:28.320
know, contracting with consultants, you sign an exclusive contract with some kind of vendor or

00:43:30.879 --> 00:43:36.639
even outsourced development. I'm not sure. I think everybody, it's more budget-constrained

00:43:36.639 --> 00:43:43.520
than optimized. Yeah, someone from the chat vibes, and I definitely agree with that.

