easily digestible by somebody who is sport fluent, but not necessarily data fluent. And,

00:48:15.679 --> 00:48:22.800
you know, like there are certain touch points within competitive sport, like the prerogative

00:48:22.800 --> 00:48:30.399
across sport is how do you win? And there are decision points like a game or a draft or free

00:48:30.399 --> 00:48:38.560
agency. Like that seems to be almost like fairly universal of how do you prepare for those

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:45.919
instances? And like, what are the best strategies? It's interesting walking this fine line of like,

00:48:45.919 --> 00:48:50.959
what is secretive or what can be shared? And I know that's with every industry too,

00:48:50.959 --> 00:48:56.239
like with pharmaceutical industries. I know they do a lot of open sharing and a lot of

00:48:56.239 --> 00:49:01.199
presentations and conferences with each other. But I'm sure there's a ton of stuff that they

00:49:01.199 --> 00:49:07.520
don't want to share with each other too. I know, Steve, you just asked a question

00:49:07.520 --> 00:49:08.879
in the chat if you want to jump in.

00:49:13.360 --> 00:49:20.959
Hello. Yeah. So interesting chat. I'm trying to get obviously a little bit more details,

00:49:21.600 --> 00:49:28.560
which is how do you, how are you supported as software engineers? Is this something do you

00:49:28.560 --> 00:49:34.879
self-support yourself? Do you have some sysadmins or are you using third parties

00:49:34.879 --> 00:49:40.080
to actually do your administration? How do you look after yourselves?

00:49:42.800 --> 00:49:46.879
Oh, great question. Are we doing a good job on that? I don't know. It's playoff season.

00:49:47.439 --> 00:49:55.199
We're very fortunate that we do have someone on our team who does take ownership of that role.

00:49:57.040 --> 00:50:04.320
For other teams, every option that you've listed, it certainly could be

00:50:05.679 --> 00:50:11.840
the direction that they choose. So it really kind of depends on do you have enough resources

00:50:11.840 --> 00:50:19.199
to support somebody who would be internal, or do you have enough time resources to self-support,

00:50:19.199 --> 00:50:25.360
or do you have enough financial resources where you could outsource it and you can

00:50:25.360 --> 00:50:30.879
allow your team to focus more on the development and data pipelining and

00:50:32.959 --> 00:50:37.439
the immediate requests that your team stakeholders may have.

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:45.600
So what proportion would you say of your, if you're assuming your group which is doing,

00:50:45.600 --> 00:50:50.159
it sounds like you're doing self-support, what percentage of time do you find is

00:50:50.959 --> 00:50:59.840
doing the data analysis and what type of time is spent building servers or configuring servers for you to use?

00:51:00.800 --> 00:51:10.239
It's pretty role-specific. So like I said, we're very fortunate to have one person on our team who

00:51:11.919 --> 00:51:19.040
spends the majority of their time in that role. But because we're so small,

00:51:19.040 --> 00:51:21.919
we have to be empowered to handle it on our own.

00:51:21.919 --> 00:51:33.760
Okay, thank you. Thank you. And there was an anonymous question as well, and I'm going to guess what one of the acronyms is, but

00:51:34.320 --> 00:51:40.399
how competitive is it to get front office, get into front office data science or software

00:51:40.399 --> 00:51:50.719
engineering roles for a sports team? Very, people say that it's very competitive, but I think that

00:51:50.719 --> 00:51:57.919
it ends up being very lucky. And as I was talking about earlier, it's supposed to be

00:51:57.919 --> 00:52:04.239
one of the more equitable ways to get into a front office or to work for a team because you're

00:52:04.239 --> 00:52:11.280
supposed to be evaluated on your skill set and not whether you've played professionally before.

00:52:11.280 --> 00:52:15.199
I certainly haven't played in the NBA before. I've never played basketball even at a

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:23.360
highly competitive level. I think that there are kind of like some secret tricks that people

00:52:25.520 --> 00:52:40.239
on the inside know. And everyone usually says that you have to build a portfolio with basketball

00:52:40.959 --> 00:52:43.600
related projects. You should have

00:52:49.439 --> 00:52:56.000
kind of an intuitive sense of like what might be useful for communicating data to a coach or

00:52:56.560 --> 00:53:03.760
or to a front office within a specific domain like salary cap or scouting.

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:13.919
But I personally didn't have a basketball portfolio. I didn't even really think,

00:53:15.040 --> 00:53:23.040
oh, like I have to work in basketball. So I think that my experience is probably

00:53:23.360 --> 00:53:36.879
different and maybe unique. It's very difficult to get a role for a front office because they

00:53:36.879 --> 00:53:42.879
just don't come up that often. And when people are hiring, I think it's kind of like the greater

00:53:42.879 --> 00:53:48.560
trend in the data science and software engineering industries now where everyone would love a senior

00:53:48.560 --> 00:53:54.159
developer or a senior data scientist, but nobody wants to hire an entry level

00:53:56.159 --> 00:54:01.760
person. And then how do you get an entry level job if that job's not advertised? Then it's

00:54:02.719 --> 00:54:07.919
what's your network? And it's a lot easier to build your network if you're already associated

00:54:07.919 --> 00:54:16.479
with basketball or you have a lot of time to work on projects in a visible way for free.

00:54:16.479 --> 00:54:24.320
And I think that that kind of shadow requirement is specifically disadvantaging women and people

00:54:24.320 --> 00:54:28.800
of color because we have different responsibilities. We have different demands on our time.

00:54:29.360 --> 00:54:38.239
And oftentimes we haven't been told that that's one of the blueprints to get a job in sports.

00:54:38.239 --> 00:54:45.040
And I just think that we as an industry need to be doing a better job of making sure that

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:54.080
like that requirement, if it has to be a requirement, that we provide kind of a

00:54:54.080 --> 00:54:59.760
development pathway that's rewarded either through a hackathon. The NBA used to have one

00:55:01.280 --> 00:55:06.639
or through women in sports data, which will have cash prizes, but to specifically target and develop

00:55:06.639 --> 00:55:16.080
those communities to mentor them and tell them specifically, this is what we want in basketball.

00:55:16.080 --> 00:55:23.840
This is what we want in football. But I don't know because teams are not going to grow

00:55:26.560 --> 00:55:33.360
in any significant sense. If you have an R and D department that's larger than the rest

00:55:33.360 --> 00:55:37.760
of basketball operations, then the people who keep the books are going to be like, well,

00:55:37.760 --> 00:55:44.639
why don't we just hire an outside organization to do this that sells the same information

00:55:44.639 --> 00:55:51.520
or does the same thing? They're not going to understand the business case for a large department.

00:55:51.520 --> 00:55:57.280
So I don't think that positions, it's not going to be a growth industry, but you can use those

00:55:57.280 --> 00:56:04.080
same skill sets to get a job for a second spectrum or for a Hawkeye or

00:56:06.560 --> 00:56:13.679
even in like traditional big tech that would love to provide services for sports.

00:56:13.679 --> 00:56:20.639
So for instance, Zach, he brought up Big Data Bowl, like that's sponsored by AWS, $100,000.

00:56:20.639 --> 00:56:25.280
And they are the named data provider. And so I think there's always going to be

00:56:26.159 --> 00:56:32.239
that pathway that will make people attracted to sports, but it's not really

00:56:34.320 --> 00:56:36.879
kind of a direct blueprint for doing it.

00:56:41.760 --> 00:56:50.239
Thank you. I see there were a lot of questions we unfortunately didn't get to within the hour.

00:56:50.239 --> 00:56:54.879
So if people are on and want to jump in and ask their question, feel free to just raise your hand

00:56:54.879 --> 00:57:03.760
right now, too, if there's anything that I missed. Trevor, I see you had asked one

00:57:05.199 --> 00:57:09.040
around measuring when you're making a difference. Do you want to jump in?

00:57:10.320 --> 00:57:17.760
Yeah. Hi, everyone. So that's always my constant question, right? So clearly,

00:57:18.560 --> 00:57:22.719
when you're doing a project, you're always asking yourself, am I making a difference

00:57:22.719 --> 00:57:28.959
or am I going to measure success, right? I mean, it's evident that more organizations,

00:57:29.600 --> 00:57:37.120
even here in Jamaica, actually getting more data science departments, hiring more analysts,

00:57:37.120 --> 00:57:44.800
it makes sense, right? But how do we justify our existence qualitatively and quantitatively?

00:57:44.800 --> 00:57:50.080
So in a sport like basketball that I like as well, is how do you know that you're making a

00:57:50.080 --> 00:57:54.719
difference in terms of the bottom line at the end of the day, if you understand what I'm asking?

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:04.560
Totally. I think that it's one of the joys and terrors of being in a data-intensive role for a

00:58:04.560 --> 00:58:14.399
team is that you can't point to, oh, we did X or we recommended Y, and now we have an NBA

00:58:14.399 --> 00:58:20.560
championship. But it really has to be, does analytics, does data and investment in data

00:58:21.280 --> 00:58:26.639
at a league level indicate that you're going to have sustained success?

00:58:29.199 --> 00:58:37.360
And I think that the investment in analytics departments and the success of the teams that

00:58:37.360 --> 00:58:44.879
have been able to do so is kind of indicative of how teams are evaluating the values that data

00:58:44.879 --> 00:58:54.239
provide. But I do think that that's really nice to say, but we also need to hold ourselves

00:58:54.239 --> 00:59:01.199
accountable of like, we're using all this time and resources. Does it contribute to winning?

00:59:01.199 --> 00:59:11.679
Does it help us make better decisions? And I think that it's almost a qualitative assessment of

00:59:13.840 --> 00:59:22.800
at certain pressure points, did we create an environment where it was easier to negotiate a

00:59:22.800 --> 00:59:36.560
trade or pull the trigger on drafting a certain player over another? Or even to the level of

00:59:37.280 --> 00:59:43.600
preparing for what happens on court, did we create an environment of, all right, we knew

00:59:43.600 --> 00:59:53.919
these tendencies, we could project this expected value. Were we able to support that in a way that

00:59:53.919 --> 01:00:00.879
it was actionable and retainable and implemented either at a player level or coaching level?

01:00:01.600 --> 01:00:04.800
Thank you. I understand. It's not an easy answer.

01:00:06.399 --> 01:00:14.399
Yeah. Thank you, Tegan. I know we're taking you out of your work during playoffs. Do you have

01:00:14.399 --> 01:00:21.439
time for one more question? Sure. Okay, awesome. Well, thank you so much for all that you do to

01:00:21.439 --> 01:00:28.080
open the doors to others to get into the sports analytics space as well. And I'm sure that you

01:00:28.320 --> 01:00:37.760
do. So just wanted to ask you, if you have any tips for us who maybe want to do something similar

01:00:37.760 --> 01:00:45.520
in our own industries? I wouldn't say that I'm a very active or fluent Twitter user, but I got some

01:00:45.520 --> 01:00:50.080
advice from my friend, Kathy Evans, who is vice president of research and development for the

01:00:50.080 --> 01:00:56.719
Washington Wizards. And also my friend, Brittany Donaldson, who is the director of research and

01:00:56.800 --> 01:01:01.919
my friend, Brittany Donaldson, who's former assistant coach for the Toronto Raptors and

01:01:01.919 --> 01:01:07.120
data analysts. And both of them are much, much better at social media than I am.

01:01:08.080 --> 01:01:13.040
But they told me, you know, like, you're one of the only women in a technical role in the NBA,

01:01:13.040 --> 01:01:19.679
and 50% of NBA teams are hiring for software developers. And like, nobody knows what that

01:01:19.679 --> 01:01:28.479
looks like, or that you can even do that as a job. And so I thought, oh, well, it just like,

01:01:28.479 --> 01:01:36.639
through being visible, like, that might help. Then I obviously would love to do that. And then

01:01:36.639 --> 01:01:43.840
it just kind of made everything else as far as the community building so much easier, because I could

01:01:43.840 --> 01:01:50.320
see a response, and I met so many people, and it was easier to develop a connection, because I

01:01:50.320 --> 01:01:54.000
could reach out to somebody, or they could reach out to me, and we could have something to talk

01:01:54.000 --> 01:02:02.800
about, whether it's like a thread that they wrote, or an invitation to a community. So yeah, at a

01:02:02.800 --> 01:02:11.520
practical level, just being visible and making friends.

01:02:15.120 --> 01:02:19.840
Awesome. Well, thank you so much for jumping on and sharing your experience with us.

01:02:20.560 --> 01:02:25.840
Really appreciate it. And thank you all for all the great questions too. If there are some that

01:02:25.840 --> 01:02:30.239
I'll miss, that I missed, I'll send them over to you, Tegan, if that's okay, through email.

01:02:30.239 --> 01:02:35.840
Of course. Yeah, thank you for having me. And yeah, if you have any questions, I'll do my best

01:02:35.840 --> 01:02:43.520
to answer them. You can always say hi on Twitter. I will never give you an opinion on a player,

01:02:43.520 --> 01:02:47.520
because I cannot afford the tampering fine, but I'll do my best.

01:02:49.040 --> 01:02:53.840
Awesome. I'll share your Twitter account right here in the chat too, if people want to go in

01:02:53.840 --> 01:02:58.239
and follow. Thank you so much. Have a great rest of the day, everybody.

01:03:00.239 --> 01:03:00.739
Bye.

